AGI - Breastfeeding seems to promote better health of children, reducing the cost of infant diseases and recourse to health care in the early years of life. This encouraging result emerges from a study published in the Plos One magazine, conducted by scientists from the Glasgow Centre for Population Health. The team, led by Tomi Ajetunmobi, examined the health, individual and economic benefits associated with breastfeeding. In particular, experts used data sets for 502.948 children born in Scotland between 1997 and 2009 and followed for a 27-month follow-up period. Previous researches have shown that breast milk is associated with a lesser disease onset in children.
&nbsp;
As part of the survey, 27 percent of cohort children were breast-feeded only, 9 percent followed a mixed diet, while 64 percent received artificial milk in the first nine weeks of life. Exclusive breastfeeding rates ranged from 13 to 45 percent respectively in the less disadvantaged areas from the economic point of view. The work shows that breast-feeding children demanded significantly lower hospital care than children who had received artificial milk.'
&nbsp;
According to experts estimates, if all mothers opted for breastfeeding, the nation would save at least ten million pounds.' Breastfeeding, the authors conclude, is a significant economic and health benefit that could more easily level health inequalities." &nbsp;

