AGI - A feast afternoon, joy, music, colors. The Stadio Olimpico in Rome was the theatre of the first World Children's Day, wanted strongly by Pope Francis>. In over 50 thousand have come from all over the world, from 101 Nations. Thousands of different shirts have coloured the sides from where the different flags were waving. One goal: to ask for peace. "Peace is always possible," says Pope Francis, who as a loving grandfather distributes sweets to the little "fan" and shows the first gesture of peace: a handshake.
&nbsp;
"You can make a real revolution with these questions and with these disturbing ones," he said to the children that from all the continents asked him questions about why war exists, how to be brothers all. "I know that you are sad for wars," "I have received children who fled from Ukraine who had so much pain for wars and some of them were wounded," "I know that you are grieved because so many of your peers cannot go to school," "there are realities that I also carry in my heart and I pray for them," Francis said.
<h2> The miracle Francis would like
The Pontiff urges them to continue to have joy "health for the soul" and to continue "to dialogue, to ask questions and to seek answers together". A child from Indonesia asks him what miracle he would like. "It's easy. That all children have the necessary to live, to eat, to play, to go to school. This is the miracle I'd like to do. The miracle that all children are happy." There are children from Palestine, Ukraine, Gaza and the Pope expresses his suffering: "This is an injustice. Unfortunately, there are so many people who have no work, have no house, dwells in the tents, many times have no food," "it is the fruit of malice, it is the fruit of the selfishness of war". "Those countries spend money to buy weapons and to destroy and there is &nbsp, which has no food," he adds.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
At the event at the Olimpico the interventions of the Minister for Sport and the Young Andrea Abodi>, accompanied by the president of the Coni Giovanni Malagò > and the president of Sport and Health Marco Mezzaroma>. A small football match was played and the Pope gave the "starting kick". To sing before the Pontiff, among others, not only Al Bano> and Renato Zero> ("Do you know what the tremarella is? I have it in front of her") also the winners of The Voice Kids, the 11-year-old Simone Grande and the 12-year-old Melissa Agliottone, the 11-year-old Matteo Roncoloni who played with his trumpet the musical theme of the film "Life is Beautiful" and the performance of Molecole show (a dancer danced suspended in the sky raised by countless colorful balloons). Then a small off-program, from a group of boys from Gaza, accompanied by Father Faltas, a blind Muslim child, who attends a Franciscan school for blind children, sang in Arabic and in Italian for peace.
&nbsp;
And then Lino Banfi>, friend of Francis ("we are both born in 1936, we are two 'reghezzi'...") and Matteo Garrone with the protagonists of his film "Io Capitano". Tomorrow the children will meet the Pope again. The appointment is in Piazza San Pietro, where after the Angelus a monologue by Roberto Benigni is planned. "Go and find your grandparents and be joyful for this day", the Pontiff greeted them by thanking the organizers (father Enzo Fortunato, coordinator, Aldo Cagnoli, vice coordinator, Marco Impagliazzo, president of the Community of Sant'Egidio, Angelo Chiorazzo, president of the Auxilium cooperative). The multicoloured fireworks, from a curve on the field, finally accompanied the exit of a smiling Bergoglio from the stadium.&nbsp;

